Overview

	This file contains various bits of information about this project that
	will be useful for the package maintainers of your Linux distro.
	Ultimately, a wiki page will be setup to contain this and additional
	information to help those that want to use this software. Please direct
	all questions to either our forums or staff via email:

		https://forums.cliquesoft.org/
		https://www.cliquesoft.org/#Contact
		support@cliquesoft.org


Building with builder

	Before any building can be performed, a profile needs to be installed
	for the software beforehand. If your Linux distro supports builder, then
	you should be able to obtain this from the repo using a command such as:

	# builder -d firefox

	An optional directory can be added at the end to specify the location to
	store the profile in. After obtaining the desired profile, it will need
	to be installed into the builder cache:

	# builder -i firefox

	If a directory was used in the first command, it needs to be used again
	with the above call too so that builder knows where to look. For ease of
	use, both of these calls can be shortened into a single command:

	# builder -d -i firefox

	Now that the profile has been installed, the software source code needs
	to be obtained. Of course, a manual download is one way. Another way is
	to use builder to fetch it for you. There are several ways to do so,
	with each being listed below along with its associated variable (and
	location):

	2. from developer    '-C dev'   URL_CODE @ package config[.1] file
	1. local directory   '-C dir'   DIR_REPO @ /etc/builder/builder.conf
	3. distro repo       '-C repo'  URL_REPO @ /etc/builder/builder.conf
	4. info file         '-C info'  URL_INFO @ /etc/builder/builder.conf

	While not all of these values may work (depending on the diligence of
	the profile creator), there are multiple sources available in the hopes
	that at least one was populated. If one fails, try another. If all the
	values fail, the source code will have to be manually downloaded. To
	attempt the above options, call builder like:

	# builder -C repo -c firefox

	This will download the source code and compile the firefox software. To
	perform the same steps, but to additionally package the software for a
	distro repository, use the '-b' action instead:

	# builder -C dev -b firefox

	Just as you can with the first two commands, either of the preceeding
	calls can optionally include a trailing directory to store files in.
	It is also possible to build multiple related software using a single
	builder profile. Take for example, the alsa project. It has two source
	codes - alsa-lib and alsa-utils. You would need to configure an 'alsa'
	builder profile using a multi-pass setup so that the first pass compiles
	alsa-lib (with config.1 > CODE='alsa-lib') and the second pass compiles
	alsa-utils (with config.2 > CODE='alsa-utils'). In this instance, you
	would also need to be one level up in the directory structure:

	# ls
	alsa-lib-1.1.4.1/   alsa-utils-1.1.4/
	# builder -b alsa


Order of operations

	Below we will list the order of operations that the builder script runs
	when compiling and optionally packaging software:

	1.  Process [/usr/local]/etc/builder and ~/.[etc/]builder configs
	2.  Adjust variable values via passed switches
	3.  System checks (parameter values, file system, failed attempts)
	4.  Install compile-time dependencies
	5.  Optionally obtain the source code
	6.  Optionally apply any patches		pwd=source code
	7.  Execute pre.compile script			pwd=source code
	8.  Generate compile process (configure)	pwd=source code
	9.  Execute post.configure script		pwd=source code
	10. Generate compile process (make *)		pwd=source code
	11. Actually compile the software		pwd=source code
	12. Copy in the 'extra' files			pwd=source code
	13. Execute post.compile script			pwd=source code
	14a. Install compiled software			pwd=source code
	14b. Separate contents into individual packages	pwd=DIR_DUMP/NAME[.TYPE]
		NOTE: can be skipped if SKIP=TRUE
	 A. Apply file/directory ownership/permissions	pwd=DIR_DUMP/NAME[.TYPE]
		NOTE: will only be executed on the last pass
	 B. Execute pre.package script			pwd=DIR_DUMP
		NOTE: apply any final file/directory ownerships/permissions now
	 C. Create the various packages			pwd=DIR_DUMP
	 D. Copy the files into the local repo		pwd=DIR_DUMP
	 E. Execute post.package script			pwd=DIR_DUMP
	20. Cleanup					pwd=DIR_DUMP
	21a. Initiate the next pass if requested
	21b. Execute cleanup script as final command	pwd=DIR_DUMP


Example directory structure

	# global config file that personalizes the global variables
	  /etc/builder/ config
	# package-specific config file			pwd=DIR_DUMP/NAME
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/config[.1,.2,...]
	# a script that will be executed to further clean up the file system
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/cleanup
	# specify command line parameters here instead of passing them
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/params
	# pre-compile script to perform adjustments	pwd=source code
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/pre.compile[.1,.2,...]
	# same as above, but run post-compile		pwd=source code
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/post.compile[.1,.2,...]
	# pre-package script to perform adjustments	pwd=DIR_DUMP
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/pre.package[.1,.2,...]
	# same as above, but run post-package		pwd=DIR_DUMP
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/post.package[.1,.2,...]
	# a flag file indicating cleanup should occur automatically
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/proper[.1,.2,...]
	# stores files not part of 'include' (e.g. httpd.conf for php compile)
	  NOTE: useful when DIRS=TRUE
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/extras/ usr/local/tce.installed/foo
	# for files like .desktop files, icons, service scripts, etc
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/include[.1,.2,...]/ [DIR_VAR]/foo.conf
	# contains any distro specific patches to be applied pre-compile
	  /var/cache/builder/ foo/patches[.1,.2,...]/ xyz_patch.cpp
	# temporary location to store any files needed by builder
	  /tmp/builder/
	# the staging location that stores the compiled/packaged software
	  /tmp/staging/
	# contains all the packaged software to be moved into an online repo
	  /tmp/repo/


Example foo/config		  NOTE: these are comprehensive or complementary

	# Toggle the execution for any of these commands
	# NOTE: when using multi-pass files (e.g. config.1, config.2), these can
	#       be used to define which pass any of these commands are executed
	#       depending on the value assigned in each config file
	CHECK=1		# make check
	CLEAN=0		# make clean; NOTE: a '2' value = 'make distclean'
	CONF=1		# configure
	PROP=0		# make mrproper
	TEST=1		# make test
	SORT=''		# indicates the package contents need sorting this pass
	# The below variable is optional and should only be used when compiling
	# more than one software with a single builder profile. For example you
	# can compile both alsa-libs and alsa-utils with a single 'builder alsa'
	# command if the config.1 CODE value is 'alsa-libs' and config.2 CODE
	# value is 'alsa-utils'. This value would uniquely identify which source
	# code directory to use per pass.
	CODE=''

	# The URL to the developers source code located in a git repo
	# NOTES:
	#     - if doing multi-pass, this needs to be in the first config file
	#     - this is optional but does allow a '-C git|dev' call
	GIT_REPO=''
	# Same as above, but the URL to a non-git (homepage) download link
	URL_CODE=''

	# If the compile type is 'custom', you need to specify all commands here
	# For example: gcc -O foo
	# NOTE: if this contains variables, still surround it with single quotes
	COMPILE=''

	# directory locations used when installing
	DIR_BIN="${DIR_INST}/bin"
	DIR_ETC="${DIR_INST}/etc"
	DIR_LIB="${DIR_INST}/lib"
	DIR_SBIN="${DIR_INST}/sbin"
	DIR_SHARE="${DIR_INST}/share"
	DIR_VAR="${DIR_INST}/var"

	# directory locations used with 'configure'
	CFG_BIN="${DIR_INST}/bin"
	CFG_DATA="${DIR_INST}/share"
	CFG_DATAROOT="${CFG_DATA}"
	CFG_DOC="${DIR_INST}/share/doc/NAME"
	CFG_DVI="${CFG_DOC}"
	CFG_HTML="${CFG_DOC}"
	CFG_INCLUDE="${DIR_INST}/include"
	CFG_INFO="${CFG_DATA}/info"
	CFG_LIB="${DIR_INST}/lib"
	CFG_LIBEXEC="${DIR_INST}/libexec"
	CFG_LOCALE="${CFG_DATA}/locale"
	CFG_LOCALSTATE="${DIR_INST}/var"
	CFG_MAN="${CFG_DATA}/man"
	CFG_OLDINCLUDE="/usr/include"
	CFG_PDF="${CFG_DOC}"
	CFG_PS="${CFG_DOC}"
	CFG_SBIN="${DIR_INST}/sbin"
	CFG_SHAREDSTATE="${DIR_INST}/com"
	CFG_SYSCONFIG=""
	# The CFG_MISC is a builder extra variable that can be used per project,
	# but will need its associated switch. So, for example, mplayer has a
	# non-standard switch to place its codecs. Simply enter:
	#   "--codec-dir='/whatever/dir'" for this variable value to use it.
	CFG_MISC=""

	# Specify compile-time package dependency list to build this software
	# (e.g. DEP_MAKE_PAK='autogen')
	DEP_MAKE_PAK=''

	# Specify run-time package dependency list for each package type:
	DEP_EXEC_BIN=''				# binaries
	DEP_EXEC_DEV=''				# development files (*.h files)
	DEP_EXEC_GIR=''				# gir files
	DEP_EXEC_LIB=''				# libraries

	FLAG_CONF='--enable-foo --disable-foo2'	# the 'configure'/'cmake' flags
	FLAG_INST='--FOO1=foo --FOO2'		# the 'make install' flags
	FLAG_MAKE='--FOO1=foo --FOO2'		# the 'make' flags

	FLAG_A32="export CFLAGS='...'
		  export CXXFLAGS='...'
		  export LDFLAGS='...'
		  export PKG_CONFIG_PATH='${PATH_PKGCFG}'"	# ARM 32bit
	FLAG_A64=""					# ARM 64bit
	FLAG_I32=""					# Intel/AMD 32bit
	FLAG_I64=""					# Intel/AMD 64bit
	FLAG_M32=""					# MIPS 32bit
	FLAG_M64=""					# MIPS 64bit
	FLAG_P32=""					# PowerPC 32bit
	FLAG_P64=""					# PowerPC 64bit
	FLAG_R32=""					# RPi 32bit
	FLAG_R64=""					# RPi 64bit
	FLAG_V32=""					# RISC-V 32bit
	FLAG_V64=""					# RISC-V 64bit


Example foo/params		  NOTE: these are comprehensive or complementary

	ARCH='i64'	# current CPU architecture being compiled (e.g. i32)
	DIRS=		# package using directory names instead of one directory
	INFOFILE=''	# if the .info is used to obtain source code
	PASS=''		# specify the number of passes to make during compile
	SKIP='TRUE'	# indicates to skip packaging until the final pass
	TRIM=''		# removes part of the name when building the package
	METHOD='default'  # specifies the type of make system to use
	WGET=''		# the location to obtain source code from

